1 About the dataset

  • The dataset consist of two subsets. One subset (dataset A) includes application data for every customer that has been given a loan in a 6 month period. The other (dataset B) contains every loan that has been given in this time and whether it has been a good loan or a bad loan.

  • The goal of this project is to identify which new applicants should be given a loan in the future or not, using the two datasets (A&B).

  • Other potential outcome from this project is to discuss any problems or limitations with the data, shortcomings of differenct analysis regime.

2 Introduction

  • This problem could be treated as an unsupervised (binary) clustering problem which a machine learning technique will be deployed or a supervised binary classification problem which will be fitted in to a logistic regression model.

  • Structure of this presentation: Datasets Overview Preprocessing Diagnostic Variable selection Modeling Optimization Discussion and comparison

Covariates with only one value will be excluded from the full dataset.

Logical covariates are converted into 0 and 1, denoting false and true, respectively. Time covariates either are treated as integer (birth day) or categorical variable (application time).

cat('logical: residence_rent_or_own, bank_account_direct_deposit')
## logical: residence_rent_or_own, bank_account_direct_deposit
dt[,':=' (residence_rent_or_own = residence_rent_or_own*as.integer(1), 
          bank_account_direct_deposit = bank_account_direct_deposit*as.integer(1))]
 
cat('categorical: email')
## categorical: email

dt[, ':=' (names=NULL,domain = as.factor(domain))] # names doesn't mean anything 

cat('time: birth_date -> age, application_when')
## time: birth_date -> age, application_when
dt[, ':=' (age = calc_age(as.Date(birth_date)),
                application_when = as.Date(application_when))]
dt[, ':=' (year = year(ymd(application_when)),month = month(ymd(application_when)), day = day(ymd(application_when)),
                dow = weekdays(dt$application_when))]
dt[, ':=' (application_when = NULL,
                birth_date = NULL,
                dow = as.integer(as.factor(dow)))]

6 Data diagnostics

For real data, one can expect various issues in the dataset listing from missing data, outliers, multicollinearity, and severe violation from normality and so on. We first start with variable visualizations.

6.1 amount required VS amount approved

plot(dt$amount_requested,dt$amount_approved,xlab ='amount_requested',ylab='amount_approved')

It shows strong collinearity between amount_requested and amount_approved.
Any requested amounts below 500 are granted. Any amounts >= 500 are either granted or reduced to 500. Some decision mechanism is already involved, might be leaky.

idx<-which(dt$amount_requested==dt$amount_approved)
idx1<-which(dt$amount_approved<=500)%in%idx
idx2<-which(dt$amount_approved>500)%in%idx

cat('target mean for unapproved loan | approved loan (<=500) | approved loan (>500)')
## target mean for unapproved loan | approved loan (<=500) | approved loan (>500)
mean(dt$flgGood[-idx]);mean(dt$flgGood[idx1]);mean(dt$flgGood[idx2])
## [1] 0.3858696
## [1] 0.4513064
## [1] 0.4489796

6.2 loan_duration VS duration approved

plot(dt$loan_duration, dt$duration_approved, xlab ='loan_duration',ylab='duration_approved')

Similarly, collinearity between loan_duration and duration_approved, any loan_duration shorter than 6 are approved, while those greater than 6 are either approved or reduced to 6, again, credit decision might be involved.

7 Preprocessingcontinued

In this part, I will tackle problems found in the above section and factorize categorical/ordinal variables.

train <- dt
  • categorical/ordinal
catNames <- c('home_phone_type','other_phone_type','how_use_money','address_zip','bank_routing_number','domain')
train <- fact_Cat(data.frame(train),catNames)
catNames <- c('email_duration','residence_duration','bank_account_duration','payment_frequency')
train <- fact2int(data.frame(train),catNames)
train <- fact_Cat(data.frame(train),catNames)
catNames <- c('bank_routing_number_edit','zipcode2','zipcode3')
train <- fact_Cat(data.frame(train),catNames)
# catNames <- c('how_use_money','domain','zipcode2','zipcode3')
# train <- OneHot(as.data.frame(train), catNames)
# train <- data.table(train)
  • reduce colinearity: drop covariates/add indicators/averaging
train$payment_amount_approved <- NULL 
train[,raw_FICO := (raw_FICO_retail + raw_FICO_telecom)/2]  
train[, flg_loan_duration :=  (loan_duration==duration_approved)*as.integer(1)]  
train[, flg_amount_requested := (amount_requested == amount_approved)*as.integer(1)]
train$duration_approved <- train$amount_approved <-  NULL
  • drop useless covariates: emails, address_zip, monthly_rent_amount, monthly_income_amount
train$bank_routing_number_edit <- NULL # train$bank_routing_number <- NULL 
train$address_zip <- NULL 
train$monthly_rent_amount <- NULL # monthly_rent_amount contradict with rent-or-own
train$monthly_income_amount <- NULL

  • generating new covariates: age, zipcode_2,zipcode_3, etc.

  • create a 10-fold cross validation set

# validation set
set.seed(1988);nfold=10
train$rand<-runif(nrow(train))
train$validationGroup <- 1
for (i in 1:nfold){
  train$validationGroup<-with(train,ifelse(rand>(i-1)/nfold & rand<i/nfold,i,validationGroup))
};train$rand <- NULL

train <- data.frame(train)
catNames <- list('residence_rent_or_own','loan_duration','domain',
  'email_duration','residence_duration','bank_account_duration','payment_frequency',
  'home_phone_type','how_use_money','zipcode2','zipcode3','month',
  'flg_loan_duration','flg_amount_requested')
for (set in catNames){
  var <- paste(c('baye^',set),collapse="|")
  tmp <- bayesEncoding(d=train,y='flgGood',vars=set, group='validationGroup')
  train[[var]] = tmp$mean_flgGood
}
catNames <- list(c('payment_frequency','zipcode3'))
for (set in catNames){
  var <- paste(c('baye^',set),collapse="|")
  tmp <- bayesEncoding(d=train,y='flgGood',vars=set, group='validationGroup')
  train[[var]] = tmp$mean_flgGood
}

8 Modeling

Common practice:

  • Logistic regression for the binary classification (main goal in this project). Classical logistic regression

Bayesian logistic regression

  • Tree-based models for tabular data (used for comparison in prediction).

Evaluation metrics: AUC (area under the ROC curve): 1 invariance of predicted probability and no need to re-balance datasets, 2 probability threshold adjustable for business purpose, e.g.false positive rate -> loss money, one may want to reduce it.

  • Classical logistic regression model

val_lr <- train[,c('flgGood','validationGroup'),with=F]  
dropfeat <- c('validationGroup','customer_id','bank_routing_number',
              'how_use_money','zipcode3') 
for (i in 1:nfold) {  
  #print(names(train[validationGroup != i, -dropfeat, with=F]))
  lr.model <- glm(flgGood ~.,
                  family=binomial(link='logit'),
                  data= train[validationGroup != i, -dropfeat, with=F])
  pred_lr <- plogis(predict(lr.model, train[validationGroup == i, -dropfeat, with=F]))
  val_lr$flgGood[val_lr$validationGroup == i] <- pred_lr
  cat("AUC for fold", i, ":",auc(train[validationGroup == i, ]$flgGood, pred_lr),"\n") 
}
